q34:
- I understand that helpdesk is the single point of contact; however, sometimes you didn't hear back from the contact you are working with for a few days. Would prefer a direct contact (an assigned individual) to communicate, once the helpdesk ticket is created.

- The front line staff of help desk and the web services department is always helpful. However, lab consultants quality varies. Some are very energetic and want to help people, some of them just don't show interest in offering help.

- next.iu.edu provides good information on what product is forthcoming or in testing. Would like to have those information being push to us, instead of need to go find out myself. Also, some of the product maybe of interest for us, e.g. soft chalk, but it is only available to IUB. 

- Is it possible to have regular news to showcase new technologies (whether instructional related or not) that different campuses have? This information will enable us to learn about what others have that work and maybe can implement it on our campus.
Wireless service can be spotty while remaining stationary in Northside Hall at IUSB. This can be frustrating when working with students who have their own laptops.

I hate the phone system.  Requiring that I be connected to my computer in order to use the phone is ridiculous.  when computers go down those on the outside have no ides why we are not answering our phones.  it results in terrible customer service

Need more improvements in following:

Adding more hot spot for Wireless connection.
Wireless connection.
Printing station.
Hall way desktops.

I had a problem with my personal computer and I decided to go to the IT center and see if they could help. I was helped right away and was very impressed with these two guys that solved the problem even though it took longer than expected. They had a great attitude and I will always remember to go there if I need anything.

Computer labs and staffing keep getting cut.  I understand that while the next Admin remodel is taking place, the EA open computer lab will be lost.  That will only leave open labs in the Library & DW as places to get computer assistance, which will make it much less convenient.  While the express stations that were added are helpful, they aren't a replacement for having a person available to assist.  I know money is tight but there seems to be money for "extras" like fancy charging stations in the library and I've heard rumors of 3-D printers which are definitely not cheap.
Lack of consistent, reliable Wi fi in classrooms in Northside hall classrooms on IUSB campus
I have received nothing short of fantastic service from our IT department. They are fast, accurate, patient with my n00b self, and fun.
failed login attempts on cellular devices for one.iu.edu .  Internet goes out a lot and it is really slow at times.

I was having an issue with downloading the free Microsoft Office onto my Mac. I chatted with an employee over instant messaging to get some help, and when I couldn't figure it out I walked straight into the UITS office and someone was helping me within minutes. I was very impressed and grateful of the nice gentleman who helped me out. Thanks guys!
IT customer service is great. I have used it quite a few times and they always are courteous and get the job done. I could not say that 3 years ago. (something changed for the better!)

Make SPSS available to faculty computers at no charge. The IUAnyWare option is not an acceptable alternative. It crashes, lags, and does not share the same properties as the desktop version. Also, the wireless service is unreliable. I regularly have to forget and reconnect my phone, laptop, and tablet to the network because they frequently say connecting without any subsequent progress.
Phones are linked to PC.  When that goes down we have no way of communicating with the outside world.
I wish designs of webpages didn't change so often.  I'm always having to relearn where things are.
We have had a drop in service for Wi Fi.  I understand that building changes cause problems, but it's inconvenient.

I requested to install SAS paying from my own account and it took me a semester working with UITS trying several times on different laptops and ends up being told I should try IUANYWARE. Come on, my student can pay $100 to install SAS on their laptop, and as a faculty it took me so much trouble and kept receiving confusing messages from different persons. I see no sincere efforts from UITS to support faculty's research needs on this campus.

I use classroom in Northside 013 IUSB. class room comptuer station seems to need some work and updates. Woris just ok also screen in room is tearing at the top. Internet in room when playing videos seems to be quirky. For the most part things are ok...
A large number of staff and students use Mac computers. Some of the computer labs should be converted to Mac computers instead of all the computer labs being PC type computers only.

I will change schools if I am forced to adopt Macintosh. Wi-fi is temperamental. Iu secure network log in does not work well with windows10. There's no it training courses available in South bend. After logging in to my umail account on my Android I can no longer sign in to the account on my windows computer.
Canvas: Pop-up materials get in the way of other applications in smaller screen environments. These are not helpful. Please stop using them.
Wireless - especially in the library. It will connect to the IU secure for awhile, but then randomly disconnect and will not connect again.

Wireless is spotty enough that it is hard to tell if it is the Apple device or the network services.  Administration Building (AI) around the conference rooms 250 / 251 and along the front side of EA.
N/A

Expanding the reach of WIFI on campus would be great! There are often times times when I am sitting in a class room and and need to look something up for the class, I am not able to connect to the wifi.

For Umail system, I hope it can be improved. Because not only me have the same problem. Once I send an email from Umail to my professors, but they said they didn't received it. I hope Umail could add a facility that show whether email receiver have received the email or not. This can add convenience for some of our students and professors.
Integration is key. Continue to reduce number of different systems, such as email.

Printing stations are convenient, however with each copy only being a few cents a piece, our printing fee per semester is absolutely outrageous!! And if we don't print the several hundred copies that that fee would cover (who's going to print several hundred pages??) we don't ever see that money!! This needs to change!

Stop changing things without improving them - One.iu.edu is definitely NOT an improvement ovver OneStart, and we were given no voice in decision and no reason for the change. I have no reason to anticipate that Canvas will be any better than OnCourse, and by the time I learn Canvas, it will probably be replaced by something else. Most of the campus computer labs for students have been closed and not replaced, which creates a real problem for students, especially since the "print to any print station from your phone or other mobile device" apparently either does not work or screws up in unpredictable ways at least as often as it works. 

And more than anything else - PLEASE talk to the faculty who actually use the classrooms before changing the classroom technology (I absolutely hate the current "tech lecterns", which have zero surface space for notes, demo materials, etc, block the students' view of the chalkboard and/or of the professor with a monitor than can't be moved, and with dismaying frequency refuses to operate some crucial piece of equipment such as the LCD projector or the document camera). I do not have a single colleague who was aware of that change until they walked into their classrooms on the first day of class, and none of them are happy about it. Forcing us to give up valuable bench space in teaching labs to laptops that are locked in place and can't be moved in order to be able to show diagrams or figures is also increedibly frustrating.

Please train support staff to support more than one system. Last summer my phone stopped working (logged out spontaneously and refused to let me log back in); I put up with not having a phone in my office for several weeks and tried everything I could think of before asking my campus IT HelpDesk for assistance, because (as I'd anticipated) what I got when I did ask for help was "Oh, you have a Mac - that's why your phone doesn't work. If you want a phone, you'll have to switch to a PC" (ignoring the fact that I'd had a functioning phone with a Mac for several months if not years previously). I get this all the time - "You can't do that" rather than "I/we don't know how to do that"....which would be less frustrating if it weren't for the fact that as mere faculty I'm not allowed administrative access to my own computer, so even if I *can* figure out how to solve a problem, I don't have the authority to change what needs to be changed in order to fix it. That policy, that only IT is ever allowed to change anything on individual faculty office machines, could be rescinded any time now.

And since I mentioned the phone system....has anybody considered the fact that now that the phones run through the computer system, every time the power goes out the phone system goes down? Which means I can't call out AND I can't get any IU Notify alerts telling me what's going on? I have to rely on random students in the hall getting messages on their smartphones and sharing those messages with me to find out if this is just a temporary issue or if my class has been cancelled. The assumption that everyone is permanently hardwired to the internet via mobile devices that always work (my whole floor of my building has no cell service, and the never-very-reliable wi-fi goes out when the power does) is simply not valid, and putting systems in place that rely on my ability to access e-mail and/or text messages in my office or in my building's basement during a tornado, for example, strikes me as not a good idea.

I struggle to get the assistance I need when I need it.  I'm constantly referred to someone else by a link or email address rather than having the service I contacted contact who needs to be contacted to address the issue.  It often feels like I'm being bounced around and what I need never gets done because it should be some other person or department handling it.

I feel that the number of emails I receive each day is far to many. In order to cut down on the emails I need to read I typically delete the UITS emails without reading them because there are so many. I do not see them as containing important information.
Some of the menu items eg: enroll or add courses are redundant and only one of them works properly.
Thank you
THE WIEKAMP BUILDING HAS VERY POOR WIRELESS NETWORK WHICH FRUSTRATES WHEN AT THE STUDENT CENTER LOUNGE.
none
Stand-up Kiosks are not helpful for disabled students who need to sit in a chair, which are not available at these kiosks.
Need better web content management system.

1) Our campus has yet to fully implement responsive web design.  This is critical given the proliferation of mobile and tablet devices.  Why isn't this a priority?
2) The WCMS is horrible!  It is difficult to use, cumbersome, and limited.  Because of that, many departments don't update their pages or if they do, they are unattractive and uninviting. There should be a folder that includes templates, buttons, rules, etc. that can easily be grabbed and adapted.  There is insufficient staff on campus to help with webpages or do training.  Even some of the local UITS pages have times included bad links, dated info, etc. 
3) I think specialized labs should supported and upgraded by UITS. 
4) Crimson is awful.
5) Students and community patrons need better mechanisms for adding money to their ids to print. 
6) Staff have not embraced Sharepoint because it is not intuitive or attractive.  I wish there was a better intranet platform. 
7) I am confused about computer builds for student labs.   Why are different software programs loaded on other campuses' lab workstations and not ours?
None at this time.

It would be beneficial if someone were to invent a Dentrix program accessible for student learning on IUanywhere.  Like the program for statistics courses.  This would be a phenomenal way to gain knowledge and to feel more confident when using the program during patient treatment.  Dental hygiene students are not allowed access to this program because of patient confidentiality/HIPAA.  Why not make a program that is consistently updated to what is used in the Dental Hygiene program but does not have real patients.  It would be greatly appreciated by students in the future.  
Jas

I'm an adjunct, and find much of the technical process here at IUSB to be difficult to understand. For example, a brand new computer lab was built in the EA-1109 lab with a pole in the middle blocking the view of the whiteboard and projector screen for fully 10% of the machines in the room.  It is good to have reliable networking but it would be even better for those 3 students to be able to see the projector screen.  Sure, it is "just 3 students" but...
Everything's great, except WiFi.  There are many many holes in service throughout the building in Northside
Outlook is a huge problem. For months, it has locked up numerous times a day and no one at the help desk seems to have a solution. I know I am not the only one.
I would in the future like it if you had sufficient browsers to read that material assigned to me on canvas

The IU IT department has been extremely supportive and very helpful!  I would give them a grade A+.  Staff are very personably, which increase there effectiveness. 

Thanks IU IT for as great job!

I have noticed problems with the network on busy weeks like the first week of the semester, midterms, and finals week. Not having reliable access to a connection or an incredibly slow, bogged down connection makes these weeks very stressful.
I like the variety that UITS provides for students and faculty. I also like how UITS is adherent to the needs of student and faculty, such as Canvas, or Box. The adaptation is really commendable.

One thing I am concerned is the workers who are to work in the Language Lab do not show up and the lab has to be closed. There have been times when I had to use the lab on the weekends but no one showed up to work. Also there were times when I needed help with the way the computer was working, but the person who is working could not help me. Usually if I had to go to the IT desk, the people there usually could help me.

If I live on campus I shouldn't have to worry about the internet suddenly going out. It has gone out in the middle of timed online quizzes before and while I've been doing homework. I suggest you make a separate, password protected Wifi connection specifically for housing so that the students there don't panic and have anxiety attacks over the fact they can't finish a quiz or turn in homework that's due in an hour.
big changes over the last few years. Special kudos to Beth and Paul for their leadership!
In the computer lab where one of my classes meets there is a column blocking the view of 3 of the computer stations.  This was poor planning when designing the room.

Half of the time computers aren't set up to go to the right printer, they will be set to go to one note or something stupid that like and then you can't change it to go to the right printer because it's not listed as an option. Also, the wifi sucks.. only works about half the time.
